`crates/steno/src/parse/` is the front end of the steno compiler: it turns `.steno` source text into `Vec<Entry>`, each holding a stroke key, raw and parsed template (`Vec<Chunk>`), `EntryFlags`, and generic metadata. Downstream consumers only ever see `Entry`/`Chunk`/`Expr`/`EntryFlags`, all defined in `mod.rs`.

Parsing is two-stage and the stage boundary is the main cross-file coupling: `source.rs::parse_source` splits the file into fenced stroke blocks plus `@`-directives, then calls `template.rs::parse_template` once per block with the joined body and a computed starting line number (`line_no + 1`, so errors point after the opening fence). `template.rs` in turn calls `expr.rs::parse_expr` for any `%(...)` computed expression, converting a `None` into a `StenoError`. A change to error-position conventions in `source.rs` (which line number is passed) directly affects where `template.rs` and `expr.rs` errors get reported, since neither of those files tracks line numbers independently.

Directive validity is centralized: `source.rs` parses `@name` syntax generically and defers to `EntryFlags::set_named` (in `mod.rs`) as the sole authority on which flag names exist — adding a flag means editing `mod.rs`, not `source.rs`. Similarly, `Expr`'s two-field shape (`a*d+b`) is defined in `mod.rs` but built only by `expr.rs`.

Invariant across the subtree: no file in this directory panics on malformed input — every parse failure surfaces as `None`/`Result::Err(StenoError)` with a 1-based line/column, using `saturating_add` arithmetic throughout `source.rs` to keep even pathological inputs panic-free.